Review for Sweetheart Deal by HappyDragon, Part 1.

https://archiveofourown.org/works/36163999/chapters/90148447

It's a good story that has quite a few flaws. But I enjoyed reading it while listening to the LA Noire OST.

I liked the interactions of the characters, the world is built well and I can feel the noir and jazz dripping from the words. The metaphors and similes never failed to be entertaining, reminding me of the few times I tried to read crime stories from pulp magazines.

I enjoyed reading Marlowe, being a tough noir detective while also having feminine traits. How she goes about things and explains what she does makes her interesting to follow.

But I have some criticisms:

-Some of the description feels unnecessary, and thus, removing it will not impact the story much. An example is in Chapter 4 with the comments on the transportation boards. I know this is for world-building purposes, but I feel if this was removed or introduced differently, nothing much would change and it would help the story's flow.

-The slang laden prose is exhausting to read. I know it's part of Marlowe's narrative voice but it can be harsh to read in long stretches. This can be compounded by someone who isn't familiar with the colloquialisms of the 20s/30s. I had to take a few breaks. This leads onto my second point.

-The plot is a bit confusing. The first chapter with Marlowe in her office, second she's walking down the street, then at a bar. The story can feel like it's bouncing all over the place with lots of words but very little plot progression. Especially because it takes seven chapters to cover one day, it feels very slow. I know slow pacing is common in the thriller genre, but I feel it could be streamlined a little.

Basically trying to find out if a story has been updated. I can check the index of the author in the OP and see if it is less than last time, but then you got authors that are anonymous, so I skip those.

If I stopped there it would be easy, but I want to watch the updates of the anonymous stories and sometimes the author index doesn't changed but his story gets updated. To find that out I have to look at the the story order under the author and if not that see if the attributes (the update notes) has changed. But then you have some authors with the same stories but just with different update notes like Dermock or departing the anthrostate. Then I have to go to the URLs and see how their order has changed.

All of this makes the code more vulnerable to false positives that come from slight url changes (someone might post the full work instead of the chapter of an A03 link). Then you have simple mistakes and shitpost threads and also author names suddenly changing like name changed daily which suddenly became changed_daily this edition.

I'm going to date myself, but do you have any familiarity at all with a furry webcomic from the 80s called "Albedo," by Steve Gallaci? The setting is hard sci-fi with faster-than-light travel and multiple interstellar polities. There are many intelligent species, all of whom came from the same planet a few centuries before, where they came to the sudden realization that their existence made no sense, and there was no fossil record. They have tentatively decided that they were all genetically engineered at some time in the unknown past and plopped down on that planet. They're all anthro versions of various Earth creatures. The main character is a somewhat Mary Sue-ish cat anthro named Erma Felna. She is in the Space Anthro military. She has adventures.

>>47060400
"Isekai" is a Japanese narrative convention, or, "trope," if you prefer, found in lots and lots of animoos and mangos. It involves characters being mysteriously transported to another world, maybe through a portal or something, maybe they just wake up there. Round trip travel is not easy. Usually the story is about their search for a way back home, though not always.

Occasionally entire cities or countries get transported forward, backward, or sideways in time, though that is a special case and is usually called an "isot" (from "Island in the Sea of Time," a sci-fi novel by one S. M. Stirling).

Bad webcomics used to be a guilty pleasure of mine. I think you're being a little too cynical. Most of it was just young people seeing a new outlet for whatever was knocking around their minds, so no wonder many of them were bad. Gamer comics, furry comics, and gamer furry comics were the background radiation of webcomics getting up to steam. Lots of edgy shit, too. Obviously.

Personally, I curse the gag comics. I was never that into them, and they became the face of webcomics. A lot of them were extremely low effort. It's pretty obvious in the ones that still survive, like XKCD and Order of the Stick. Literally just stick figure comics. The only guy I know for a fact got ahead on business skill was that Dinosaur Comics guy. And that's another example of a shitty comic hoisted onto a pedestal. But the ads he used to sell to webcomic authors were a smart move, and they occasionally helped me find new comics.

Anyone who got into webcomics to make it big was an idiot. But I don't think that was anyone, really. Maybe some had hopes, but only Penny Arcade made it happen in any big way. But yeah, comics are hard. Terrible pacing is the thing that kills most long form webcomics, in my opinion.
